TY  - JOUR
T1  - Fiscal Foresight and Information Flows
AU  - Leeper, Eric M.
AU  - Walker, Todd B.
AU  - Yang, Shu-Chun Susan
Y1  - 2013/05/01
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/05/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8337
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1115
EP  - 1145
VL  - 81
IS  - 3
KW  - News
KW  - anticipated taxes
KW  - non-fundamental representation
KW  - identified VARs
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA8337
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - News?or foresight?about future economic fundamentals can create rational expectations equilibria with non-fundamental representations that pose substantial challenges to econometric efforts to recover the structural shocks to which economic agents react. Using tax policies as a leading example of foresight, simple theory makes transparent the economic behavior and information structures that generate non-fundamental equilibria. Econometric analyses that fail to model foresight will obtain biased estimates of output multipliers for taxes; biases are quantitatively important when two canonical theoretical models are taken as data generating processes. Both the nature of equilibria and the inferences about the effects of anticipated tax changes hinge critically on hypothesized information flows. Different methods for extracting or hypothesizing the information flows are discussed and shown to be alternative techniques for resolving a non-uniqueness problem endemic to moving average representations.
ER  - 

